                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/4245.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-19T21:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 19, 1912—9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Read a paraphrase of your June 19, 2 p.m., to Minister for Foreign Affairs and am
                    also sending him an urgent note based thereon. He promised to communicate
                    immediately with the Secretary of War and have the most urgent and explicit
                    instructions sent to commanding officer in the sense of your telegram.
                    Imperative to take Ciudad Juárez as soon as possible and he saw no way to avoid
                    battle. He said a siege is impossible as the Government has not troops
                    sufficient to surround city; unless American Government can cooperate by
                    isolating it on American side, preventing entry of provisions and other
                    supplies, siege would be ineffective. He thinks rebels will try to provoke
                    American action by firing wilfully into American territory. He declared it was
                    his most earnest desire to avoid repetition of unfortunate events of previous
                    fighting at Juárez, not only because of claims and other annoyances, but also
                    from realization of international obligations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schuyler.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
